Objective
Verify that the detection module can passively sniff the network interface, capture live ARP reply packets, and correctly extract and display the source IP and MAC address from each captured packet in real time.

Test Code
 
# TC-02: ARP Detection Test
# Tester  : Mayank Sharma
# Purpose : Verify detection module captures ARP replies
# Run     : sudo python3 tests/test_detect.py
 
from scapy.all import sniff, ARP
 
print("Testing Detection Module...")
 
def detect(packet):
    if packet.haslayer(ARP) and packet.op == 2:
        print(f"[!] ARP Reply: {packet.psrc} is at {packet.hwsrc}")
 
sniff(filter="arp", prn=detect, store=0)
 

How The Code Works — Step by Step
1.	sniff(filter="arp", prn=detect, store=0) — Starts a passive listener on the network interface. Captures only ARP packets. store=0 means packets are not stored in memory — processed live.
2.	For every captured ARP packet, Scapy automatically calls the detect() callback function.
3.	packet.haslayer(ARP) — Confirms the packet is an ARP packet.
4.	packet.op == 2 — Filters for ARP Reply packets only. op=1 is ARP Request, op=2 is ARP Reply.
5.	Prints source IP (psrc) and source MAC (hwsrc) from each reply — these are the fields used to detect spoofing in the main tool.

